    <section>
        <h3>Misconception #1</h3>
        <div class="question-box">"If I delete something, it's gone forever."</div>
        <div class="fragment box-blue">
            <p><strong>❌ FALSE</strong></p>
            <hr style="border-color: rgba(255,255,255,0.3);">
            <p>Screenshots, cached copies, and archives mean nothing is truly deleted. Once it's online, assume it's permanent.</p>
        </div>
    </section>

    <section>
        <h3>Misconception #2</h3>
        <div class="question-box">"It's just a joke — people shouldn't be so sensitive."</div>
        <div class="fragment box-blue">
            <p><strong>❌ FALSE</strong></p>
            <hr style="border-color: rgba(255,255,255,0.3);">
            <p>Intent doesn't equal impact. A "joke" can still cause real harm, and you're responsible for how your words affect others.</p>
        </div>
    </section>

    <section>
        <h3>Misconception #3</h3>
        <div class="question-box">"Nobody important will ever see my posts."</div>
        <div class="fragment box-blue">
            <p><strong>❌ FALSE</strong></p>
            <hr style="border-color: rgba(255,255,255,0.3);">
            <p>Future employers, university admissions, and even strangers can find your digital footprint. Assume everything is public.</p>
        </div>
    </section>

    <section>
        <h3>Misconception #4</h3>
        <div class="question-box">"Being anonymous online protects me from consequences."</div>
        <div class="fragment box-blue">
            <p><strong>❌ FALSE</strong></p>
            <hr style="border-color: rgba(255,255,255,0.3);">
            <p>Anonymity is not immunity. Serious cases can be traced by police, and the harm you cause is still real even if you hide.</p>
        </div>
    </section>
</section>
